title: For Sale:  Japanese Arisaka Type 99 short rifle
postcontent: Japanese Arisaka Type 99 short rifle. Japanese military WW2 battle rifle.  Built in mid to late 1944.  Serial Number #1682, series #34.   Built at the Toyo Kogyo arsenal in Hiroshima, Japan.  Original factory red toned wood finish.  Bolt action with tight and smooth working receiver and plum handled bolt. Barrel bore and cartridge chamber in great condition with nice rifling.  Chambered in 7.7mm with 5 round internal box magazine.  Original as issued finish on metal and wood, not modified nor sporterized and in good solid firing condition.  Bolt is serial number #311 and does not match receiver number.  Stock is solid and not cracked but has some marks from use and all metal parts have nice dark aged patina with some slight frosting and freckling.  The mum has been fully defaced as per US military regulations at the end of the war for surrendered and some captured weapons. This rifle is a late war transition gun and does not have some of the features found on early made rifles.  This rifle does have it's original and correct short cleaning rod.  No correct sling but reproductions are available to make this a great display rifle for the military arms collector or shooter.  Ammo is still available for these rifles.  Person to person cash sale only and sorry no shipping.  Must be of legal age to purchase.  Feel free to contact me by email or phone if you need more info or would like more photos at .  Thanks for your interest.

title: For Sale:  SIG P226 MK25 9MM done up right + SRT trigger + xtras!!!
postcontent:
I have for sale a very special SIG P226 MK25 that I purchased last summer.  It is an incredible pistol yes, but this one is even BETTER than new.  Yes it has the original awesome specs like Sig Nite Sites, phospate coated internals, accessory rail, hicap mags, and all the goodies - but mine is done up right!
I have had the SIG "short reset trigger" or SRT installed, so that is a huge upgrade!  I will include the original trigger as well.
I also have a small DeSantis leather holster for it, a slightly larger DeSantis leather holster, and a Blackhawk molded Kydex holster for it. The leather holsters have been broken in with Blackrock leather rub with the gun left in when treated, while wrapped in wax paper. The 3 holsters are important to the gun since the MK25 only fits a few of the holsters that regular P226's use, since the MK25 has a true Picatinny rail and not the smaller Sig specific rail on ordinary versions of P226's. 
I have 3 original SIG mags, and one 20 round mag from MecGar who makes the mags for SIG (which is the 18 round MecGar mag that has the +2 mag bumper on it - you can see them on any website).
When the trigger work was done, I also had the feed ramp polished and the barrell hood coating stripped and polished. As you know, the black coating on SIG barrel hoods scrape off with even minimal use, so I have mine stripped down and polished - as the polished stainless steel is a much cleaner look.
The MK25 has Hogue overmolded black grips on it, I will also include the original grips.
Gun is a pure joy to shoot, I have only shot it three or four times at the indoor range, mostly has been sitting in my safe.  It isn't new as it has about 300 or 400 rounds through it, but that is barely even a break in period. You will love this gun!
Price for basic gun is about $925, plus holsters ($125), plus SRT trigger work ($100), extra mags ($35), plus feed ramp & hood work ($100), plus Hogue grips ($20). So I have approx $1300+ total into this rig. If you buy the gun I will also be happy to sell you 9mm ammo at my cost, FMJ and/or hollow point defense ammo.

title: For Sale:  Sporterized Schmidt-Rubin 1889 ($150)
postcontent:
Very accurate rifle.  Typical swiss quality, high quality machining.  Very smooth bolt and a great two stage trigger that breaks clean.  The rifle is chambered for 7.5x53.5mm Swiss. 

This rifle will chamber and fire the common 7.5x55mm GP11 swiss round.  But it’s not recommended as pressure is a lot higher with that round.  Many folks fire that round through these rifles with no issues at all, but I still wouldn’t feed an 1889 a steady diet of them.  

Sporterized stock, that has slight finger/hand groves for your trigger hand.  12 round box magazine.  Excellent bore, that’s bright.  Strong land and grooves, I don’t think too many rounds have been fired through her.   Very neat and unique rifle.   

Serial # dates this rifle to 1892, so this is considered an antique, so I can legally ship this rifle if you’re willing to pay for the shipping cost.  

More info on these amazing high quality rifles can be found at the website below:
http://www.swissrifles.com/sr/
